<paragraph id="486336C0FF8BE041FFC8F597FC877EC8" blockId="48.[125,879,374,431]" box="[125,879,407,431]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FFC8F597FE027EC8" box="[125,490,407,431]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">
<typeStatus id="97678862FF8BE041FFC8F597FF5B7EC9" box="[125,179,407,430]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Type</typeStatus>
species. 
<taxonomicName id="8FDC4D43FF8BE041FEA3F597FE027EC8" authority="Schotte &amp; Kensley, 2005" authorityName="Schotte &amp; Kensley" authorityYear="2005" box="[278,490,407,431]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Heterodina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mccaini" status="sp. nov.">Heterodina mccaini</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="619B57A9FF8BE041FE46F597FDBB7EC8" box="[499,595,407,431]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, by present designation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="486336C0FF8BE041FFC8F5D2FC757E8D" blockId="48.[125,925,466,490]" box="[125,925,466,490]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FFC8F5D2FEAF7E8D" box="[125,327,466,490]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Additional species.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="8FDC4D43FF8BE041FEE6F5D2FC717E8D" authority="(Kensley and Schotte, 1987)" baseAuthorityName="Kensley and Schotte" baseAuthorityYear="1987" box="[339,921,466,490]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Cassidinidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mosaica">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FEE6F5D2FDD37E8D" box="[339,571,466,490]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Cassidinidea mosaica</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2C4D4B31FF8BE041FDF9F5D2FC787E8D" author="Kensley B &amp; Schotte M" box="[588,912,466,490]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" pagination="216 - 247" refId="ref26224" refString="Kensley B, Schotte M. 1987. New records of isopod Crustacea from the Caribbean, the Florida keys, and the Bahamas. Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington 100 (1): 216 - 247." type="journal article" year="1987">Kensley and Schotte, 1987</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="486336C0FF8BE041FFC8F61EFF0E7D51" blockId="48.[125,230,542,566]" box="[125,230,542,566]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FFC8F61EFF0E7D51" box="[125,230,542,566]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="486336C0FF8BE041FFC8F64EFD257C60" blockId="48.[125,1172,590,872]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FFC8F64EFF577D01" box="[125,191,590,614]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">
<collectingRegion id="8A18F822FF8BE041FFC8F64EFF527D01" box="[125,186,590,614]" country="Maldives" name="Maale" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Male</collectingRegion>
.
</emphasis>
Body dorsoventrally somewhat compressed, length more or less twice maximum width; with membrana cingulata; integument smooth or finely tuberculate; margins with fringe of setae. Cephalon embedded in pereonite 1; eyes dorsal. Epistome visible in dorsal view. Coxal extension on ventrum of pereonite 1 absent; pleonal tergite absent. Exopod of uropod very small, set into margin of endopod. Pleon with free lateral margins. Pleotelson triangular, apex extending slightly beyond uropod.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="486336C0FF8BE041FF2DF710FB7C7C0F" blockId="48.[125,1172,590,872]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Pleopod 1 with endopod reduced, about half length and half width of exopod. Pleopod 2, appendix masculina short and broad. Exopod of pleopod 3 without suture; both rami of pleopods 4 and 5 lamellar or with very weak folds. Penes long, tapering and basally fused.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="486336C0FF8BE041FFC8F78BFD157CA4" blockId="48.[125,1171,907,963]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FFC8F78BFF3D7CC4" box="[125,213,907,931]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Female.</emphasis>
Similar to male except in genitalia. Mouthparts not metamorphosed. Marsupium formed by two opposing pockets opening at sternite 4.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="486336C0FF8BE041FFC8F7F7FF347B68" blockId="48.[125,220,1015,1039]" box="[125,220,1015,1039]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FFC8F7F7FF347B68" box="[125,220,1015,1039]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="486336C0FF8BE041FFC8F028FD9B7946" blockId="48.[125,1172,1064,1569]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">
This genus exhibits a unique mix of characters which may be found singly in other ‘‘subfamily’’ groups. It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="8FDC4D43FF8BE041FDAFF048FD4B7B07" authorityName="Hansen" authorityYear="1905" box="[538,675,1096,1120]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Cassidinidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FDAFF048FD4B7B07" box="[538,675,1096,1120]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Cassidinidea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which it most resembles at first glance, by having the cephalon set into the first pereonite instead of having expanded lateral margins; the penes, instead of being entirely fused, are basally fused; and the appendix masculina, instead of being long and acute, is short and broad. These characters were mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation id="2C4D4B31FF8BE041FFC8F0C8FEC47B87" author="Bruce NL" box="[125,300,1224,1248]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" pagination="1077 - 1173" refId="ref24754" refString="Bruce NL. 1994 b. The Cassidininae Hansen, 1905 (Crustacea: Isopoda: Sphaeromatidae) of Australia. Journal of Natural History 28: 1077 - 1173." type="journal article" year="1994">Bruce (1994b)</bibRefCitation>
, who therein stated the need for a new genus to accommodate 
<taxonomicName id="8FDC4D43FF8BE041FBACF0C8FE507A67" authority="Kensley and Schotte, 1987" authorityName="Kensley and Schotte" authorityYear="1987" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Cassidinidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mosaica">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FBACF0C8FB7C7B87" box="[1049,1172,1224,1248]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">C. mosaica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="2C4D4B31FF8BE041FFC8F0E8FE507A67" author="Kensley B &amp; Schotte M" box="[125,440,1256,1280]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" pagination="216 - 247" refId="ref26224" refString="Kensley B, Schotte M. 1987. New records of isopod Crustacea from the Caribbean, the Florida keys, and the Bahamas. Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington 100 (1): 216 - 247." type="journal article" year="1987">Kensley and Schotte, 1987</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, which is herein transferred to the new genus. The morphology of the cephalon of the new genus is shared with the 
<taxonomicName id="8FDC4D43FF8BE041FD6BF108FC657A47" authorityName="Hilgendorf" authorityYear="1885" box="[734,909,1288,1312]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Leptosphaeroma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FD6BF108FC657A47" box="[734,909,1288,1312]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Leptosphaeroma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group of Cassidininae (
<bibRefCitation id="2C4D4B31FF8BE041FF33F128FEC37A27" author="Bruce NL" box="[134,299,1320,1344]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" pagination="1077 - 1173" refId="ref24754" refString="Bruce NL. 1994 b. The Cassidininae Hansen, 1905 (Crustacea: Isopoda: Sphaeromatidae) of Australia. Journal of Natural History 28: 1077 - 1173." type="journal article" year="1994">Bruce, 1994b</bibRefCitation>
), which possess in contrast short, unfused penes and expanded antennular peduncles. These latter two traits are also common to those species in the 
<taxonomicName id="8FDC4D43FF8BE041FC6BF148FBA07A07" authorityName="H. Milne Edwards" authorityYear="1840" box="[990,1096,1352,1376]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Cassidina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FC6BF148FBA07A07" box="[990,1096,1352,1376]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Cassidina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group as defined by 
<bibRefCitation id="2C4D4B31FF8BE041FEAFF168FE2F7AE7" author="Bruce NL" box="[282,455,1384,1408]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" pagination="1077 - 1173" refId="ref24754" refString="Bruce NL. 1994 b. The Cassidininae Hansen, 1905 (Crustacea: Isopoda: Sphaeromatidae) of Australia. Journal of Natural History 28: 1077 - 1173." type="journal article" year="1994">Bruce (1994b)</bibRefCitation>
, in which however the cephalon is not set into pereonite 1. For the same reason the new genus does not fall within Bruce’s 
<taxonomicName id="8FDC4D43FF8BE041FCF9F188FC3D7AC7" authorityName="Hansen" authorityYear="1905" box="[844,981,1416,1440]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Cassidinidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FCF9F188FC3D7AC7" box="[844,981,1416,1440]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Cassidinidea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group and thus remains unallied within the ‘‘subfamily’’ Cassidininae. It may indeed signify a fourth such grouping. The structure of the brood pouch, however, is identical to that of 
<taxonomicName id="8FDC4D43FF8BE041FBB6F1C8FB647A87" authorityName="Hansen" authorityYear="1905" box="[1027,1164,1480,1504]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Cassidinidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FBB6F1C8FB647A87" box="[1027,1164,1480,1504]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Cassidinidea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, i.e. formed by two opposing pockets and different from those in 
<taxonomicName id="8FDC4D43FF8BE041FC19F1E8FBB37967" authorityName="Hilgendorf" authorityYear="1885" box="[940,1115,1512,1536]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Leptosphaeroma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FC19F1E8FBB37967" box="[940,1115,1512,1536]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Leptosphaeroma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="8FDC4D43FF8BE041FFC8F209FF0F7946" authorityName="H. Milne Edwards" authorityYear="1840" box="[125,231,1545,1569]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Cassidina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FFC8F209FF0F7946" box="[125,231,1545,1569]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Cassidina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as described by Harrison (1984).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="486336C0FF8BE041FFC8F24CFF157903" blockId="48.[125,253,1612,1636]" box="[125,253,1612,1636]" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8BE041FFC8F24CFF157903" box="[125,253,1612,1636]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="486336C0FF8BE040FFC8F27DFF137FC6" blockId="48.[125,1023,1661,1685]" lastBlockId="49.[138,251,137,161]" lastPageId="49" lastPageNumber="1259" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">
Species of the genus are known at present from 
<collectingCountry id="30CB7650FF8BE041FD01F27DFD1179F2" box="[692,761,1661,1685]" name="Belize" pageId="48" pageNumber="1258">Belize</collectingCountry>
and the Persian Gulf. 
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8AE040FF3FF489FF137FC6" box="[138,251,137,161]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="1259">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="486336C0FF8AE040FF3FF4B9FDBD7F95" blockId="49.[138,1184,185,242]" pageId="49" pageNumber="1259">
The generic name is derived from the Greek ‘‘hetero-’’ (different or other), plus the 
<emphasis id="7AA8EAD2FF8AE040FBEDF4B9FF527F95" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="1259">suffixdina</emphasis>
, indicating the subfamilial affinity.
</paragraph>
